It seems like you forgot a translation here:

  
    
  
    

  
  This file contains bidirectional Unicode text that may be interpreted or compiled differently than what appears below. To review, open the file in an editor that reveals hidden Unicode characters. Learn more about bidirectional Unicode characters


  


    
      
        Suggested change
        
          
    

        
      
    
    
      
          
            
                        "importError": "Import failed. Please try again or contact an administrator for assistance."
          
          
            
                        "importError": "Import fehlgeschlagen. Bitte versuche es nochmal oder kontaktiere einen Administrator für Hilfe."

Small typo

  
    
  
    

  
  This file contains bidirectional Unicode text that may be interpreted or compiled differently than what appears below. To review, open the file in an editor that reveals hidden Unicode characters. Learn more about bidirectional Unicode characters


  


    
      
        Suggested change
        
          
    

        
      
    
    
      
          
            
                 * Imports all team of the source exercise into the destination exercise
          
          
            
                 * Imports all teams of the source exercise into the destination exercise

Good finding! The reason why this check was not there previously was that this was a global existence query that returned whether this team short name exists among all exercises. But now that we have eased the unique constraint and the check has become exercise-specific, we can indeed add the authority check you proposed (but use isAtLeastTeachingAssistantForExercise since TAs are also allowed to use it).
I don't know if its necessary, but maybe we want to add that the source exercise has to be in the same course to prevent questions.

Good point. I'm not sure if users would assume that you can import teams from a different course since different courses also have different students usually but I agree that being as explicit as possible is best. I'll add it.
